{"title_page": "Gadag-Betageri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Gadag-Betageri\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = kn \n| other_name              = Krutapura\n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = [[City]]\n| image_skyline           = Veera Narayana Temple, Gadag.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Veeranarayana Temple\n| pushpin_map             = India Karnataka#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Karnataka, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|15.4167|N|75.6167|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bayaluseeme]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Gadag district|Gadag]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = City Municipal Council (CMC)\n| governing_body          = Gadag-Betageri CMC\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 54.01\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 654\n| population_total        = 172,813\n| population_metro        = 367,258\n| population_as_of        = 2010\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = 4657\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Kannada]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 582 101-103\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 08372\n| registration_plate      = KA-26\n| website                 = {{url|www.gadag-betagericity.mrc.gov.in}}\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-KA]]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Gadag-Betageri'''  is a city municipal council in [[Gadag district]] in the state of [[Karnataka]], [[India]]. It is the administrative headquarters of [[Gadag District]]. The original city of Gadag and its sister city Betageri (or ''Betgeri'') have a combined city administration. The municipality of Gadag-Betageri has a population of  172,813 and an area of 54.0956&nbsp;km\u00b2. [[Kanaginahal]] of Gadag is the birthplace of the first co-operative society in [[Asia]]. The temples of [[Veera Narayana Temple, Belavadi|Veera Narayana]] and [[Trikuteshwara]]<ref>[http://www.nkpost.kar.nic.in/tourismgadag.htm \"Gadag\"] www.nkpost.kar.nic.in. Retrieved September 9, 2012</ref> are places of religious and historic importance.\n\n\nThe twin city municipality is situated 80&nbsp;km from [[Dharwad]] and 60&nbsp;km from [[Hubballi]], and lies on the Gutti-Vasco National Highway.  Badanekai bajji is the most loved food in Gadag. And you will get here the best Girmit in the world.\n\n==Gadag style of architecture==\n\n[[File:Pillars at Sarasvati Temple in Gadag.JPG|thumb|left|upright| Gadag style Ornate pillars at Sarasvati Temple, [[Trikuteshwara]] temple (complex) at Gadag]]\nThe ''Gadag style of Architecture'',<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.tifr.res.in/~vahia/SN-search.pdf\n|title=In search of Indian records of Supernovae\n|publisher=\n|accessdate=2009-03-12\n|format=PDF}}</ref> marked by ''Ornate pillars with intricate sculpture'',<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.templenet.com/Karnataka/kalyani_chalukya.html\n|title=Kalyani Chalukyan & chanakya temples\n|publisher=\n|accessdate=2009-03-12}}</ref> originated during the period of the [[Western Chalukya]] (or Kalyani Chalukyas) king ''Someswara I'', and it flourished for a period of 150 years (During {{CE|1050}} to {{CE|1200}}) during which period some 50 temples were built; some examples being:\nThe Trikuteshwara temple complex at Gadag,\nThe [[Kasivisvesvara temple, Lakkundi]],\nThe [[Doddabasappa Temple]] at [[Dambal]],\nThe Amriteshwara temple at [[Annigeri]],\netc.\n\n==Gadag inscription==\n* The 'Gadag inscription'<ref name=\"maharashtra.gov.in\">{{cite web\n|url= http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/pdf/gazeetter_reprint/History-I/chapter_9.pdf\n|title=CHAPTER 9. THE CALUKYAS AND THE KALACURYAS OF KALYANI. HISTORY \u2013 ANCIENT PERIOD, Chalukya\n|publisher=\n|accessdate=10 March 2009\n|format=PDF}}</ref>  of [[Vikramaditya VI]], records that ''Taila took the head of '''Panchala''' by the terror of the pride of his arm in battle''.\n\n* The inscription<ref name=\"maharashtra.gov.in\"/> reveals that the battle was fought on the bank of the Godavari & ocean river and a certain Keshava (son of Madhava), fought in the battle and ''won Taila\u2019s admiration''.\n* At the command of Sattiga (Satyashraya) in 1006 A.D., a Lenka Keta fell fighting at the battle of '''Unukallu''', probably against the [[Cholas]]. An inscription',<ref name=\"maharashtra.gov.in\"/> dated in ''Saka 930 (1008 A.D.)'' of the reign of ''Satyashraya'' refers to the siege of the agrahara Kaldugu in the '''Belvola 300''' by ''Desinga'' and the destruction of the forces because of the treachery of king ''Perggade''.\n* The inscription<ref name=\"maharashtra.gov.in\"/> of Ballala recounts his victory as \"And by force, he, the strong one, defeated with cavalry only, and deprived of his sovereignty, the general Brahmana whose army was strengthened by an array of elephants and who acquired 60 tusked elephants with a single tuskless elephant, when, on account of an insult, he was tearing the royal fortune from the family of the [[Kalachuris of Kalyani]].\"\n{{clear}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2011}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Gadag-Betageri had a population of 172,813. Males constitute 86,165 of the population and females 86,648. Gadag-Betageri has an average literacy rate of 85.56%. The Sex ratio is about 1006 females per 1000 males to females. 18,419 of the population is under 6 years of age.\n\n[[Kannada]] is the main and widely spoken language, [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]] are spoken and understood by few people.\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box\n| location = Gadag (1981\u20132010, extremes 1932\u20132012)\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 34.5\n| Feb record high C = 37.7\n| Mar record high C = 40.0\n| Apr record high C = 41.1\n| May record high C = 41.7\n| Jun record high C = 40.6\n| Jul record high C = 34.9\n| Aug record high C = 35.4\n| Sep record high C = 37.8\n| Oct record high C = 35.6\n| Nov record high C = 37.2\n| Dec record high C = 34.1\n| year record high C = 41.7\n| Jan high C = 30.1\n| Feb high C = 32.8\n| Mar high C = 35.7\n| Apr high C = 37.2\n| May high C = 36.4\n| Jun high C = 31.0\n| Jul high C = 28.9\n| Aug high C = 28.7\n| Sep high C = 30.0\n| Oct high C = 30.4\n| Nov high C = 29.7\n| Dec high C = 28.9\n| year high C = 31.6\n| Jan low C = 16.3\n| Feb low C = 18.2\n| Mar low C = 20.9\n| Apr low C = 22.4\n| May low C = 22.4\n| Jun low C = 21.7\n| Jul low C = 21.2\n| Aug low C = 20.9\n| Sep low C = 20.7\n| Oct low C = 20.5\n| Nov low C = 18.3\n