ds for Spencer Tracy]]\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestActor 1928\u20131940}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actor 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation masculine 1946\u20131959}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actor}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActorMotionPictureDrama 1943\u20131960}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tracy, Spencer}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:American Academy of Dramatic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:Best Actor BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actor Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Broadway theatre people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:Ripon College (Wisconsin) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "84.13.198.88", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spencer_Tracy"}
{"title_page": "Telus Corporation", "text_new": "'''Telus Corporation''' (''also referred to as Telus Corp'') is a [[publicly traded]] Canadian multinational [[holding company]] offering a range of [[telecommunications]], [[Healthcare industry|health]], [[safety]], and [[Security alarm|security]] products and services.  The company's corporate offices are located at 510 West Georgia Street, 7th Floor in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia in Canada.  It is listed with the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] ([[TSX]]: [https://web.tmxmoney.com/quote.php?locale=en&qm_symbol=T T]) and the [[New York Stock Exchange]] ([[NYSE]]: [https://www.nyse.com/quote/XNYS:TU TU]).  The company operates [[TELUS Communications Inc.|Telus Communications Inc.]], which offers telephony, television, data and [[Internet]] services, [[Telus Mobility]], a division that offers wireless services, [[Telus Health]], which operates companies that provide health products and services, and [[Telus International]] which operates worldwide, providing multilingual customer service outsourcing and digital IT services.\n\n== Timeline ==\n'''1990'''\n\nTelus Corporation is established and becomes the parent company of [[Alberta Government Telephones]] (AGT).  Sale of Telus shares raised CA$896 million and was at the time the largest initial public offering in Canadian history.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.itu.int/newsarchive/wtsa2000/english/media/timeline.pdf|title=Historical Timeline of Canadian Telecommunications Achievements|last=|first=|date=|website=ITU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1991'''\n\nThe Government of Alberta sold its remaining shares of Telus for CA$870 million.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n'''1995'''\n\nTelus Corporation acquires [[Edmonton Telephones ]] (ED TEL Inc) from the city of [[Edmonton]] Alberta for CA$467 million.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n'''1996'''\n\nTELUS becomes the company's \"master brand\" bringing its products, services, and companies under one unified identity.  The TELUS \"master brand\" introduced, bringing products and companies under one unified identity.  The brands ED TEL and AGT are retired.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n'''1997'''\n\nThe [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) provides Telus  with approval to start multimedia service trials in Edmonton and Calgary.\n\n'''1998'''\n\n'''BCT.TELUS COMMUNICATIONS INC.''' is incorporated and certified in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] on October 26, 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/3HL5xT1YMgami4OKYagsiS/736846db00ed29c852ec167537da7795/TELUS_Corporation_-_Certificate_of_Incorporation_-_Oct_26__1998.pdf|title=Incorporation Certificate|last=|first=|date=|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1999'''\n\nOn January 21, 1999, [[BC Tel|BC Telecom]] shareholders, upon the unanimous recommendation of its board of directors overwhelmingly voted to merge with Telus Corporation\u00a0who had earlier in the week on January 19, 1999 received similar approval from its shareholders.  The US based carrier [[GTE]] who had owned 56% of BC Telecom would retain 26% of the new company. The merger was worth CA$8 billion, had a combined work force of 25,000 employees, and created Canada's second largest telecommunications company behind [[Bell Canada]].  This effectively may have been the precipitous that would redraw the map for Canada telecommunications industry, which until now had major players who were part of the [[Stentor Alliance]] and constricted within their traditional provincial boundaries and facing increasing outside pressures brought upon them by the industry\u2019s deregulation. Initially the merger was registered as BCT.Telus Communications Inc. and later the new company adopted the Telus name and moved its corporate offices to BC Tel\u2019s former headquarters in Vancouver, British Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/1fXXmewnvYOqsMqeC6SYAO/15292652c7de1dd0ab0f6c08c19fb935/Proxy_Circular_BC_Telecom_and_TELUS.pdf|title=BC Tel - Telus Shareholder Meetings|last=|first=|date=1998-12-08|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/b-c-telecom-rings-in-new-era-in-merger-with-telus-1.192993|title=B.C. Telecom rings in new era in merger with Telus|last=|first=|date=1999-01-22|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''2000'''\n\nOn May 3, 2000, BCT.TELUS COMMUNICATIONS INC. becomes '''TELUS CORPORATION'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/WPIdncjrUWog0I4Esaoau/81bafb8c374d29c8039e33b5cd00d74b/TELUS_Corporation_-_Certificate_of_Name_Change_-_May_3__2000.pdf|title=Telus name change|last=|first=|date=|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2000 Telus Corporation announced an offer to purchase [[Clearnet Communications|''Clearnet Communications Inc''.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/5rpOo6EjGoqEGiO4A2aWW6/3a95559506140bb88920c21e82d2bb65/Offer_to_purchase_CLEARNET.pdf|title=Telus offer to purchase Clearnet|last=|first=|date=2000-08-21|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> for CA$6.6 billion in cash and stock.  The purchase was completed on October 19,  2000, and at that time provided Telus Mobility with the largest block of available wireless spectrum in Canada, serving approximately 700,000 users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/telus-completes-clearnet-acquisition/article4168331/|title=Telus completes Clearnet acquisition|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2004'''\n\nIn May 2004, [[Verizon Communications, Inc.]] informed the Telus Corporation board that it wanted to sell its 21% minority stake in Telus.  In December 2004, Verizon sold its share to institutional investors for an estimated value of CA$2.3 billion.  Under the terms of the agreement, Verizon paid Telus a non-refundable fee of US$ 125 million, and agreed to let Telus continue to have exclusive rights to the Verizon trademarks in Canada, and to software and technology it had acquired under an existing relationship.  Verizon also agreed to provide Telus with upgrades and support for software and technology it had licensed which allowed seamless single-rate roaming across North America.  Both companies said they would continue their business relationship and a co-operation with respect to the sharing of cross-border services.  The terms of the agreement also released Telus from its non-compete obligation against Verizon in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/verizon-reveals-plan-to-sell-23-billion-telus-stake-in-offering/article4091839/|title=Verizon reveals plan to sell $2.3-billion Telus stake in offering|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n'''2007'''\n\nIn December 2007, ''6886116 Canada Ltd.'' which was an indirect wholly-owned subsidiary of Telus Corporation, offered to purchase for cash all the common shares of Emergis Inc. for CA$8.25 each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/63OoEGnkFU2oMwiAkqycYU/a2d8f0c6eb5171edcfb17cfa16276c2c/Offer_to_purchase_Emergis.pdf|title=Offer to purchase Emergis|last=|first=|date=2007-12-11|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  The offer to purchase all of the outstanding common shares was completed on January 17, 2008 for CA$763 million.  The company was rebranded to ''Telus Health'' and divided into three segments; ''Telus Health Solutions, Telus Assyst Real Estate,'' and ''Telus Financial Solutions''.\n\n'''2008'''\n\nIn March 2008, Telus Corporation launched [[Koodo Mobile|''Koodo Mobile'']], a discount brand designed to appeal to the youth segment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/telus-targets-youth-with-new-koodo/article1351525/|title=Telus targets youth with new Koodo|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2011'''\n\nIn April 2011, Telus Corporation re-introduced [[Clearnet (Telus Mobility)|''Clearnet'']] as a discount brand in [[Western Canada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/telus-delivers-low-key-launch-of-clearnet-discount-brand/article575348/|title=Telus delivers low-key launch of Clearnet discount brand|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2012'''\n\nIn June 2012, Telus Corporation decided to stop activating customers under the ''Clearnet'' brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobilesyrup.com/2012/06/03/clearnet-once-again-decides-to-stop-activating-new-clients-existing-customers-will-join-telus/|title=CLEARNET, once again, decides to stop activating new clients, existing customers will join TELUS|date=2012-06-03|website=MobileSyrup|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2013''' \n\nIn October 2013, Telus Corporation received Industry Canada approval to purchase [[Public Mobile|''Public Mobile'']], acquiring 280,000 customers in [[Ontario]] and [[Quebec]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/tech_news/2013/10/23/telus_gets_federal_blessing_to_acquire_new_player_public_mobile.html|title=Telus buys Public Mobile in surprise move|date=2013-10-23|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''\n\nIn March 2014, Telus Corporation made the decision to shutdown ''Public Mobile'' stating the need to move its customers from an outdated network and to ensure the survival of its brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/telus-to-shut-public-mobile-s-small-outdated-network-1.2590467|title=Telus to shut Public Mobile's \"small, outdated\" network|last=|first=|date=2014-03-28|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The move would anger affected customers who would need to purchase new cellphones to migrate onto the Telus [[4G]] network, and would create further criticism from consumer advocates and further fuel the ongoing debate about the lack of competition in the industry in Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/teluss-decision-to-shut-public-mobile-angers-consumers/article17703328/|title=Telus\u2019s decision to shut Public Mobile angers consumers|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2017'''\n\nIn October 2017, Telus International announced that it had signed a deal to initially purchase a 65% stake in '''''Xavient Information Systems''''', an information technology consulting firm headquartered in [[California]], with the right to acquire the remaining interest on or before December 31, 2020 for a total of US$ 250 million.  At the time Xavient had a workforce of 8,000 employees located in the United States and India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/telus-acquires-xavient-information-systems-for-us-250m-1.900024|title=Telus acquires Xavient Information Systems for US$250M - BNN Bloomberg|last=Press|first=The Canadian|date=2017-10-30|website=BNN|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''\n\nIn January 2018, Telus Corporation announced that it had acquired the [[AlarmForce]] operations and assets for Western Canada only, for approximately CA$66.5 million from [[BCE Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telus.com/en/about/news-and-events/media-releases/telus-acquires-alarmforce-operations-in-western-canada-and-welcomes-39000-alarmforce-customers-in-bc-alberta-and-saskatchewan|title=TELUS acquires AlarmForce operations in Western Canada|website=TELUS|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Telus Health announced it had purchased 30 elite medical clinics which operate under the '''''Medisys''''', '''''Copeman Healthcare''''' and '''''Horizon Occupational Health Solutions''''' brands accross Canada for over CA$ 100 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/national/telus-jumps-into-business-of-health-clinics-buys-national-chain|title=Telus jumps into business of health clinics, buys national chain|website=Vancouver Sun|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''2019'''\n\nIn August 2019, Telus Corporation announced that it had purchased '''''Farm At Hand''''', a farm management platform that allows farmers to track and manage farm inventory.  The company was branded as \"Farm AT Hand ''driven'' by TELUS\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2019/08/telus-acquires-farm-at-hand-company/|title=Telus acquires Farm at Hand company|date=2019-08-29|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, it was announced that Telus Health had a deal to acquire the virtual health platform '''''Akira Health''''' which offers a healthcare app, as well as in-person healthcare clinics.  The terms of the deal were not disclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://betakit.com/akira-health-acquired-by-telus-health/|title=Akira Health acquired by Telus Health|date=2019-08-12|website=BetaKit|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Telus Corporation announced that it had entered into an agreement to purchase the Canadian operations and assets of [[ADT Inc.]], a US-based company, owned by equity firm [[Apollo Global Management]] for approximately US$527 million (CA$700 million).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-01/telco-operator-telus-buys-adt-s-canadian-unit-for-527-million|title=Telco Telus to Buy ADT\u2019s Canada Unit for $527 Million|date=2019-10-01|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en}}</ref>  It was announced in November 2019 that the transaction had been completed, adding to the company approximately 500,000 customers and a workforce of approximately 1,000 employees across Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telus.com/en/about/news-and-events/media-releases/telus-announces-agreement-to-acquire-canadian-operations-of-adt|title=TELUS announces acquisition of Canadian operations of ADT|website=TELUS|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.securitysales.com/news/adt-sell-canadian-operations-telus/|title=ADT to Sell Canadian Operations to Telus Corp.|date=2019-10-01|website=Security Sales & Integration|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  The company was branded \"ADT ''by'' TELUS\".\n\nIn December 2019, Telus Corporation acquired the [[Alberta]] based '''''Decisive Farming''''', a company dedicated to increasing farming profitability, sustainability, and technology ease-of-use with a single integrated platform for the farm's primary operating system.  This was the second Telus Corp agriculture acquisition.  Financial terms were not disclosed.  The company was branded \"Decisive Farming ''driven by'' TELUS\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realagriculture.com/2019/12/telus-acquires-decisive-farming/|title=Telus acquires Decisive Farming|website=RealAgriculture.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2019, Telus Corporation announced that it would acquire a 100% stake in '''''Competence Call Center'''''  (CCC) for approximately CA$ 1.3 billion (consisting of debt and equity) through its subsidiary Telus International, growing the subsidiary to about 50,000 workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2019/12/04/1956543/0/en/TELUS-Corporation-announces-agreement-to-acquire-Competence-Call-Center-through-TELUS-International.html|title=TELUS Corporation announces agreement to acquire Competence Call Center through TELUS International|last=Inc|first=TELUS Communications|date=2019-12-04|website=GlobeNewswire News Room|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on February 4, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telus.com/en/about/news-and-events/media-releases/telus-corporation-completes-acquisition-of-competence-call-center-through-telus-international|title=TELUS completes acquisition of Competence Call Center|website=TELUS|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Telus Health announced that it had acquired '''''DirectAlert''''' in Quebec, and expansion of its '''''LivingWell Personal Medical Alert Services''''' (PERS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bctechnology.com/news/2019/12/11/TELUS-Health-Announces-Acquisition-of-DirectAlert-(in-Quebec)-and-National-Expansion-of-Its-LivingWell-Companion-Personal-Medical-Alert-Services.cfm?v=1|title=TELUS Health Announces Acquisition of DirectAlert (in Quebec) and National Expansion of Its LivingWell Companion Personal Medical Alert Services|website=www.bctechnology.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Finances ==\nFor the fiscal year 2019, Telus Corporation reported earnings of CA$5.554 billion, with an annual revenue of CA$14.658 billion, an increase of 8.8% over the previous fiscal year. Telus Corp shares traded at its all-time high stock closing price of $20.89 on February 12, 2020. Telus Corp operates the largest telecommunications company (Telus Communications Inc.) in Western Canada and the second largest in Canada.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/TU/telus/stock-price-history|title=TELUS - 24 Year Stock Price History {{!}} TU|website=www.macrotrends.net|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable float-left\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Revenue<br> in mil. CA$\n!Net income<br> in mil. CA$\n!Total Assets<br> in mil. CA$\n!Price per share<br> in US$\n!Employees\n|-\n|2019<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://assets.ctfassets.net/rz9m1rynx8pv/4ilx6plw1Pb60EcskiUBzq/e685a08070f4ed3a435c962e0882331e/TELUS_2019_Annual_MD_A_and_Financial_Statements.pdf|title=Telus 2019 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=2019-12-31|website=CTF Assets|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n|14,658\n|1,780\n|37,975\n|14.7800<ref name=\":0\" />\n|65,600<ref name=\":3\" />\